  "id": "phekb-atopic-dermatitis-meds",
  "source": "phekb",
  "source_id": "atopic-dermatitis-algorithm",
  "name": "Atopic Dermatitis - Medication Query",
  "description": "Tests ability to find atopic dermatitis patients by searching for AD-related medication prescriptions. This covers the medication component of PheKB algorithm Path 1 (diagnosis + meds) and critically tests whether LLMs can identify patients managed with topical therapies alone. AD medications include topical corticosteroids (hydrocortisone, triamcinolone), calcineurin inhibitors (tacrolimus, pimecrolimus), antihistamines (cetirizine, diphenhydramine, hydroxyzine), and oral corticosteroids (prednisone) for flare management.",
  "prompt": "Find all medication orders for atopic dermatitis treatments including hydrocortisone cream, cetirizine, diphenhydramine, and prednisone.",
  "prompts": {
    "naive": "Find all medication orders for atopic dermatitis treatments including hydrocortisone cream, cetirizine, diphenhydramine, and prednisone.",
    "expert": "I need to find patients prescribed medications commonly used for atopic dermatitis management. The treatment approach typically involves topical corticosteroids like hydrocortisone cream for skin inflammation, oral antihistamines such as cetirizine (Zyrtec) and diphenhydramine (Benadryl) for itch relief, and oral corticosteroids like prednisone for managing severe flares. Search MedicationRequest resources for the specific RxNorm product codes. Note that these medications are not exclusively used for atopic dermatitis -- antihistamines and prednisone have many indications -- but they form the standard treatment ladder for AD. Some patients are managed entirely by their primary care provider with these over-the-counter and prescription medications without ever receiving a formal dermatology diagnosis."
  },
